  <p class="instrument-tag">INSTRUMENT 006 — THE MEASURING FIELD — MERIDIAN — 2026-07-01</p>
  <h1>The Fairness Trap</h1>
  <p class="subtitle">
    COMPAS recidivism prediction, Broward County, Florida, 2013–2014 — general recidivism (2-year) —
    n = {totalN.toLocaleString()} (Black + White defendants from ProPublica's 7,214-person dataset) —
    two definitions of fairness — one mathematical constraint
  </p>

  <p class="lead">
    In May 2016, ProPublica published evidence that the COMPAS recidivism scoring tool was racially
    biased: Black defendants who did not go on to reoffend were falsely labeled "high risk" at nearly
    twice the rate of white defendants. Northpointe (the maker of COMPAS) replied that the tool was
    fair: for any given score level, the rate of actual recidivism was the same regardless of race.
    Both were correct. Alexandra Chouldechova proved in 2017 why: when base rates of recidivism
    differ between groups, no scoring tool can simultaneously satisfy both definitions of fairness
    unless it achieves near-perfect accuracy. The conflict is not political. It is mathematical.
  </p>

  <div class="two-col">
    <!-- Left: Confusion matrices -->
    <div class="panel">
      <p class="panel-label">COMPAS predictions vs. actual outcomes (2-year follow-up)</p>
      <div class="matrices-row">
        <div class="matrix-wrap" set:html={bMatrixSVG} />
        <div class="matrix-wrap" set:html={wMatrixSVG} />
      </div>
      <p style="font-size:0.78rem;color:#888;margin-top:14px;line-height:1.5;">
        Confusion matrices from ProPublica methodology (Larson et al., 2016).
        "High risk" = COMPAS score medium or high (≥ 4 of 10).
        Red cells = false positives — defendants wrongly labeled as likely to reoffend.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Right: Bar charts + theorem -->
    <div class="panel">
      <p class="panel-label">Same data, two measurements, two verdicts</p>
      <div set:html={barChartSVG} />

      <div class="theorem-block" style="margin-top:18px;">
        <p class="theorem-title">CHOULDECHOVA (2017) IMPOSSIBILITY THEOREM</p>
        <p>
          If base rates differ (<code>p<sub>B</sub> ≠ p<sub>W</sub></code>) and a classifier achieves
          <strong>predictive parity</strong> (equal PPV), then
          <strong>classification parity</strong> (equal FPR) cannot simultaneously hold — except for a
          perfect classifier (FPR = FNR = 0 for all groups).
        </p>
        <p>
          Formal result: if base rates differ (<code>p<sub>B</sub> ≠ p<sub>W</sub></code>), no classifier can
          simultaneously achieve (1) equal FPR, (2) equal FNR, and (3) equal PPV — unless accuracy is perfect.
          Any two of the three can be satisfied; the third must yield. This is not a design choice; it is
          a mathematical consequence of different underlying prevalence.
        </p>
        <p>
          COMPAS's data: base rates {pct(bBase)} (Black) vs. {pct(wBase)} (White); FPR gap of {pp(bFPR - wFPR)};
          FNR gap of {pp(wFNR - bFNR)} (opposite direction); PPV gap of {pp(bPPV - wPPV)}.
          Northpointe minimized the PPV gap (predictive parity). ProPublica highlighted the FPR gap
          (equal error rates). Both were measuring real properties of the same classifier.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="finding-box">
    <p class="kicker">FINDING</p>
    <p>
      <strong>Both ProPublica and Northpointe were correct</strong> — using their chosen metrics.
      ProPublica measured false positive rates: Black defendants were flagged as high-risk without
      reoffending at <strong>{pct(bFPR)}</strong>, vs. <strong>{pct(wFPR)}</strong> for white defendants.
      Northpointe measured predictive value: COMPAS predicts recidivism with equal accuracy by race
      (<strong>{pct(bPPV)}</strong> vs. <strong>{pct(wPPV)}</strong> PPV).
    </p>
    <p>
      Chouldechova's theorem explains the coexistence: the base rate of actual recidivism differs
      by group (<strong>{pct(bBase)}</strong> for Black defendants, <strong>{pct(wBase)}</strong> for
      White defendants in this sample). Any calibrated scoring tool applied to a population with
      unequal base rates will produce unequal error rates. The COMPAS disparity is a consequence of
      calibration — not a deviation from it.
    </p>
    <p>
      This is not a calibration <em>gap</em> (a tool performing worse than it claims). It is a
      calibration <em>trap</em>: the criterion by which the tool is judged determines the verdict.
      Choosing which fairness criterion to enforce is a political decision that the technical
      specification cannot make.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Who pays</h2>

  <div class="stakes-grid">
    <div class="stake-card">
      <p class="stake-title">Pretrial detention</p>
      <p>
        A high-risk COMPAS score increases the probability of pretrial detention. Of the 805 Black
        defendants wrongly labeled high-risk, each faced a statistically higher chance of being held
        before trial — and potentially losing employment, housing, or family stability as a result.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="stake-card">
      <p class="stake-title">Sentencing</p>
      <p>
        In <em>State v. Loomis</em> (Wis. 2016), the Wisconsin Supreme Court upheld COMPAS use in
        sentencing while requiring a warning that it may not be used as "the determinative factor."
        The court also noted COMPAS cannot be tested because its algorithm is proprietary.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="stake-card">
      <p class="stake-title">Jurisdictional scale</p>
      <p>
        COMPAS and similar tools are used in hundreds of U.S. jurisdictions. Partnership on AI (2021)
        documented rapid expansion through "reform" mandates. The EU AI Act (2024) classifies
        criminal-justice risk scoring as high-risk AI; it bans "criminal predisposition" profiling
        as an unacceptable risk.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>The instrument series — six instruments</h2>

  <table class="pattern-table">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>#</th>
        <th>Tool</th>
        <th>Designed for</th>
        <th>Fails on</th>
        <th>Who pays</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>001</td>
        <td>AI text detectors</td>
        <td>Native English writers, vendor test corpora</td>
        <td>NNES students under academic assessment</td>
        <td>Students facing disciplinary action</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>002</td>
        <td>Benford's First-Digit Law</td>
        <td>Multiplicative, unbounded financial data</td>
        <td>Bounded election precinct vote counts</td>
        <td>Democratic legitimacy claims</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>003</td>
        <td>C2PA provenance chain</td>
        <td>Closed professional newsroom pipelines</td>
        <td>Open social media, adversarial actors</td>
        <td>Journalists' safety, courts</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>004</td>
        <td>Last-digit uniformity test</td>
        <td>Financial transactions (no rounding convention)</td>
        <td>Clinical BP measurement, survey age reporting</td>
        <td>Clinical data integrity, demographic research</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>005</td>
        <td>AI capability benchmarks</td>
        <td>Controlled lab evaluation, uncontaminated data</td>
        <td>Commercial leaderboard optimization</td>
        <td>Researchers, policymakers, the public</td>
      </tr>
      <tr class="highlight-row">
        <td>006</td>
        <td>Recidivism risk scoring (COMPAS)</td>
        <td>Equal predictive accuracy across groups</td>
        <td>Cannot satisfy both fairness criteria simultaneously when base rates differ</td>
        <td>Black defendants wrongly flagged; democratic accountability</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p style="font-size:0.85rem;color:#555;max-width:720px;margin-top:8px;">
    Instrument 006 extends the series in a new direction: not a calibration gap (tool performing
    worse than claimed) but a calibration trap — a mathematical impossibility built into the
    fairness criteria themselves. The tool cannot satisfy both, and the choice of which to prioritize
    is a value judgment the specification cannot make.
  </p>

  <div class="sources">
